\section{Components and Format of the Balance Sheet}
The balance sheet is the usual place to start analyzing a company. It can provide information about future earnings potential. \\
\hfill \\
The balance sheet discloses what a entity owns (assets) and what it owes (liabilities) at a certain point in time. Which is why it is often referred to as a statement of financial position. \\
\hfill \\

%%ADD MORE HERE
The \textbf{report format} lists assets, liabilities and equity in a single column. \\
\hfill \\
The \textbf{account format} follows the pattern of the traditional general ledger accounts, with the assets as the left and liabilities and equity at the right of a central dividing line. \\
\hfill \\
The grouping of various classes of assets and liabilities results in a balance sheet format known as the \textbf{classified balance sheet}. \\
\hfill \\


